Kuwait arrests suspects after mosque bomb attack
Kuwait City: Kuwait has declared an "all-out confrontation" with terrorism after an Islamic State suicide bomber struck a Shi'ite mosque in the Gulf state's capital during Friday prayers, killing 27 people.
Health Minister Ali al-Obaidi told Kuwait Television the number of dead had risen to 27 in addition to 227 wounded in the first suicide attack on Shi'ite mosques in the oil-rich emirate.
The toll in the attack, carried out during the Muslim holy fasting month of Ramadan, is one of the largest in Kuwait's history.
The interior ministry said suspects had been held for questioning, but did not specify the number or provide any details.